function’s scope, even after the outer function has returned. It captures that lexical environment. For example: \\n```js\\nfunction outer() {\\n  let count = 0;\\n  return function inner() {\\n    count++;\\n    return count;\\n  };\\n}\\nconst fn = outer();\\nconsole.log(fn()); // 1\\nconsole.log(fn()); // 2\\n```”\\n\\nQ2: “What is the difference between `var`, `let`, and `const`?”\\nCandidate: “`var` is function-scoped and is hoisted; `let` and `const` are block-scoped and not initialized until their declaration is evaluated. `const` creates a read-only reference, so you cannot reassign it, though you can mutate objects.”\\n\\n3. React.js Questions\\n\\nQ3: “How do you manage state in a functional React component?”\\nCandidate: “We use the `useState` hook. For example:\\n```js\\nconst [count, setCount] = useState(0);\\n```\\nWe call `setCount(newValue)` to update it, which re-renders the component.”\\n\\nQ4: “Describe the purpose of `useEffect` and give an example.”\\nCandidate: “`useEffect` lets you run side effects after render, like data fetching or subscribing to events. Example:\\n```js\\nuseEffect(() => {\\n  fetch('/api/data')\\n    .then(r => r.json())\\n    .then(data => setData(data));\\n}, []); // empty deps: runs once on mount\\n```”\\n\\n4. RESTful APIs Questions\\n\\nQ5: “Design a RESTful endpoint to create and retrieve user profiles. What HTTP methods and status codes would you use?”\\nCandidate: “POST /users – creates a new user, returns 201 Created with the new user object.  \\nGET /users/{id} – retrieves user by ID, returns 200 OK with the user object or 404 Not Found if no such user.  \\nFor errors, use 400 Bad Request for validation failures.”\\n\\n5. Experience-Based Questions\\n\\nQ6: “Tell me about a challenging bug you encountered and how you resolved it.”\\nCandidate: “In my last project, a React component was re-rendering infinitely because I had forgotten to include a dependency in the `useEffect` dependency array. I debugged it using React DevTools, identified the missing dependency, updated the array, and added unit tests to catch similar issues in the future.”\\n\\n6. Qualifications-Based Questions\\n\\nQ7: “Why are you interested in this role and how does your background align with our requirements?”\\nCandidate: “I’ve spent 4 years building front-end applications with React and TypeScript. Your company’s focus on scalable web apps and microservices aligns with my experience. I’m excited to contribute my skills in JavaScript performance optimization and API design.”\\n\\n7. Candidate Questions\\n\\nCandidate: “Could you tell me about the team structure and growth opportunities?”\\nInterviewer: “We have cross-functional teams of 5–7 engineers. You’ll pair with a senior engineer and have quarterly goals for career development.”\\n\\n8. Closing\\n\\nInterviewer: “Thank you, John. We’ll review your responses and get back to you within a week.”\\nCandidate: “Thank you for your time, Jane. I look forward to hearing from you.”\\n\\n9. Notes and Next Steps\\n- All responses recorded.\\n- Candidate shows strong fundamentals in JavaScript and React.\\n- Next step: technical take-home exercise.\\n\\nEnd of Interview Transcript\\n```\"}"}
